s of “race” has been chronic in Canadian history, and that the law itself was once instrumental in creating these circumstances. The book concludes with a controversial discussion of current directions in Canadian law and their potential impact on Canada’s future as a multicultural society.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aDiscrimination racialexDroitxCas, Études dexCanada. 0aDiscrimination racialexDroitxHistoirex20e siéclexCanadaxCanadaxRelations interethniquesxCanada. 0aRace discriminationxCasesxLaw and legislationxCanada. 0aRace discriminationxLaw and legislationxHistoryx20th centuryxCanada. 0aRace discriminationxLaw and legislationzCanadavCases. 0aRace discriminationxLaw and legislationzCanadaxHistoryy20th century. 4aHistory: Canadian History. 4aLaw. 4aPolitical Science. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Discrimination & Race Relations.2bisacsh1 aWalker, James W. St.G., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724040uhttps://doi.org/10.51644/978088920566640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780889205666423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780889205666/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  a978-3-11-127724-0  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010b2010  aGBV-deGruyter-alles